{{Orphan|date=May 2011}} {{Chinese name|[[Zhuang (surname)|Chuang]]}}
'''Chuang Chi-fa''' (also known as Zhuang Jifa; {{zh|莊吉發}}; born 24 May 1936) is a Taiwanese historian who studies Chinese history, in particular [[Manchuria|Manchu]] history. Chuang is one of the few linguistics researchers with a mastery of the [[Manchu language]].
His 1982 book "Qing Gaozong shiquan wugong yanjiu" (researching the [[Qianlong Emperor]]'s "[[Ten Great Campaigns]]") was called a ''tour de force'' by Yingcong Dai of William Paterson University.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dai|first=Yingcong|year=2004|title=A Disguised Defeat: The Myanmar Campaign of the Qing Dynasty|journal=Modern Asian Studies|publisher=Cambridge University Press|volume=38|pages=145–189|doi=10.1017/S0026749X04001040|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=190987|quote=In 1982, Zhuang Jifa (Chuang Chi-fa) of the National Palace Museum of Taipei published his tour de force, Qing Gaozong shiquan wugong yanjiu, which has a chapter on the Myanmar campaign}}</ref> With [[Ch’en Chieh-hsien]] he was one of the first historians to research the Manchu language documents in the Qing dynasty archives at the National Palace Museum.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Elliott|first=Mark C.|date=June 2001|title=The Manchu-Language Archives of the Qing Dynasty and the Origins of the Palace Memorial System Late Imperial China|publisher=The Johns Hopkins University Press|volume=22|issue=1|pages=1–70|issn=1086-3257|doi=10.1353/late.2001.0002|url=http://muse.jhu.edu/login?uri=/journals/late_imperial_china/v022/22.1elliott.pdf}}</ref>
==Early life== Chuang was born in [[Nanzhuang, Miaoli|Nanzhuang]] [[Township (Republic of China)|township]] of [[Miaoli County]], [[Taiwan]]. His parents died when he was young, and he was adopted by a family and taught under strict doctrines that made him into the person he is today. He graduated in 1956 from the [[National Taipei University of Education]] and in 1969 from the [[National Taiwan University]].<ref>http://r8.ntue.edu.tw/elite/01/01-43.htm</ref>
==Career== Chuang teaches and studies modern Chinese history, Chinese minorities history, and Manchu history (his main focus).<ref>http://r8.ntue.edu.tw/elite/01/01-43.htm</ref> He was a researcher at the [[National Palace Museum]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hrc.ntu.edu.tw/thci/Author.aspx?id=73413 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722235807/http://www.hrc.ntu.edu.tw/thci/Author.aspx?id=73413 |archivedate=2011-07-22 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Bartlett|first=Beatrice S|title=Monarchs and Ministers: The Grand Council in Mid-Ch'ing China, 1723-1820|url=http://publishing.cdlib.org/ucpressebooks/view?docId=ft287004wt;chunk.id=0;doc.view=print|year=1991|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley}}</ref>
Chuang has taught at [[Tamkang University]], [[Soochow University (Taiwan)|Soochow University]], [[National Taiwan Normal University]], and [[National Chengchi University]].
